creator: J. S. Fletcher
description:
LibriVox recording of The Borough Treasurer by J. S. Fletcher.

Read in English by MaryAnn Spiegel.

Messrs. Mallalieu and Cotherstone were outsiders who had built a prosperous business in Highmarket and even been elected as Mayor and Treasurer of the borough. But when an ex-detective moves to town, 30 years of respectability is suddenly threatened by revelations from the past. (Summary by MaryAnn)

For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording.

For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org. Download M4B Part1(145mb) Download M4B Part2(73mb)

title: The Borough Treasurer

reviews.reviewbody: blah blah blah blah etcetera ad infinitum.  Another detective story that could have been written in 3/4 of the chapters of the total here.  Too much redundancy, given too many clues as to who the "bad guy" is, fits and starts rather then interesting twists and turns.  I did not finish it, my illnesses are leaving me in agitated melancholia. I hope i do listen to end later and am surprised for a change.  Now only if the greatest detective/mystery writer of all time: Agatha Christie was in the public domain, and mostly female readers at librivox read her mystery detective stories that always end with the villein being the least suspected...sigh.  What was the book she wrote where a nun is found out to be the murderer in the end?-- dahszil, male, usa
reviews.reviewtitle: another nice read by MaryAnn but....

reviews.reviewbody:
If you enjoy classic era detective stories then Fletcher will generally provide some fun - and so he  does here.  Many of Fletcher's trademarks show themselves - the northern provincial town, the retired detective, the men with a dark past and (of course) a little romance.

The reading is very good.  If you enjoy detective stories then give it a go.

Okay, maybe this should have been shorter, but I'd also argue it should have been happier too.  I just don't like the way it ended.  The story was okay tho.  I listened to this a while back, and I forgot the story, so listened to it again.  Ah, that's why I forgot it so quickly.  

But Fletcher is a good writer, so I did enjoy the book mostly, just annoyed at the ending.

Reader and recordings were fine.
